+## Task Routing Tiers
+
+Before any implementation, classify the task by tier. Tier determines DID and Stage 1.5 requirements.
+
+| Tier | Criteria | DID Required? | Stage 1.5? |
+|------|----------|---------------|------------|
+| **0** | Docs only, single file, no `src/` changes | No | No |
+| **1** | Single file in `src/`, < 50 LOC, low risk | No | Yes |
+| **2** | Multi-file or architectural change | Yes — spec only, blind derivation | Yes |
+| **3** | Load-bearing, security, or governance change (AGENTS.md, SPEC.md) | Yes — full impl, blind derivation | Yes |
+
+**Tier 2/3 DID flow:** Agent A (Gemini) proposes → Agent B (Claude) derives independently (no peeking) → human reconciles → go.
+
+---
+
+## Entropy Gate
+
+Part of Stage 1.5. Every task gets an entropy score before planning begins.
+
+| Assumption type | Points |
+|----------------|--------|
+| Critical | 3.0 |
+| High Impact | 1.5 |
+| Low Impact | 0.5 |
+
+**Entropy > 10 = BLOCKED.** The task must be decomposed by the human Architect into subtasks each scoring ≤ 10. Do not plan, do not write code. Hard stop.
+
+---
+
 ## Stage 1.5 — Assumption Ledger
 
 For all Tier 1+ tasks, you must generate a **Section 27 Assumption Ledger** before planning.
